"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383918","Home Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>Rule 35 of the Detention Centre Rules 2001 requires doctors working in immigration removal centres to report to the Home Office if they have concerns about the case of any particularly vulnerable detainee in order that the appropriateness of their continued detention can be reviewed.</p><p>A Home Office audit of Rule 35 compliance was undertaken in 2014 and a summary of the audit’s findings will be published in due course.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-06-25T15:50:04.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383918/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383918/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-18","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will commission an audit of reports submitted by healthcare professionals in Immigration Removal Centres under Detention Centre Rule 35 to maintain compliance with policy on the detention of victims of crime.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","3223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383919","Home Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>In the six months to the end of March 2015 there were 11 grants of asylum, humanitarian protection, discretionary leave or another form of protection, for Yemeni nationals.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-06-25T15:38:44.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383919/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383919/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383919/answer/previousversion/7792","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-18","Refugees: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Yemenis have been granted refugee leave since the beginning of the present political and military crisis in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","3193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383920","Home Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and can only be collated at disproportionate costs.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-06-25T15:39:01.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383920/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383920/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383920/answer/previousversion/7799","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-18","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications made by asylum seekers under Article 8 of Schedule 1 of the Human Rights Act 1988 were upheld by the courts in each year since 2000.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","3157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383921","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-25","<p>The UK Government’s expenditure on malaria is provided through: malaria-specific bilateral projects and programmes; bilateral support to health systems and service delivery; UK Government contributions to multilateral and global initiatives that work on malaria prevention and treatment; and by supporting malaria related research. The UK’s Framework for Results for malaria in the developing world set out a methodology for monitoring the Government's spending on malaria. The estimated UK spend on malaria prevention, control and treatment between 2008/09 and 2013/14 was:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>£ million</p></td><td><p>Total malaria spend</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>138</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>194</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>306</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>253</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>313</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>536</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are unable to specify future spending on research or treatment of malaria, as a spending review will take place later this year that will determine the future expenditure allocations across the Department.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-06-25T16:34:53.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383921/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383921/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-18","Malaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funding her Department plans to provide for (a) research on and (b) treatment of malaria until 2020.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","3060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383922","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-23","<p>Over the last six years my Department has provided £7.6 million to the International Labour Organisation (ILO) for specific programmes where this represents value for money. DFID is currently funding programmes delivered by the ILO in India, Bangladesh and Nepal.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening","3052","2015-06-23T12:32:11.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383922/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383922/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-18","International Labour Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 10 June 2015 to Question 1293, in what countries her Department is working on projects with the International Labour Organisation; and what the value of her Department's funding is for each such project.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","3056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383923","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-23","<p>Over the last six years my Department has provided £7.6 million to the International Labour Organisation (ILO) for specific programmes where this represents value for money. DFID is currently funding programmes delivered by the ILO in India, Bangladesh and Nepal.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening","3056","2015-06-23T12:32:10.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383923/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383923/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-18","International Labour Organisation: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 10 June 2015 to Question 1293, what funding her Department has provided to International Labour Organisation programmes in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","3052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383924","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-25","<p>DFID occupies two buildings in the UK, one in Whitehall, London and the other in East Kilbride. We hold the leasehold on both properties and no rent is paid.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-06-25T16:35:40.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383924/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383924/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-18","Department for International Development: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which buildings occupied by her Department are owned or part-owned privately; what the total value is of the rent paid to private landlords for the use of such buildings for official duties; and to whom such rent is paid.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383925","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-25","<p>DFID provided to Yemen £59.1 million of bilateral aid in 2012-13, £81.4 million in 2013-14 and £67.0 million in 2014-15. Our assistance helped meet urgent humanitarian needs, deliver basic services, and support political and economic reform.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>On Friday 19 June the Secretary of State announced a further £40 million of humanitarian assistance for Yemen for 2015, which will provide Yemenis affected by the crisis with emergency shelter, healthcare, water and food assistance, as well as supporting UN work to co-ordinate the humanitarian response.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-06-25T16:35:31.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383925/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383925/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-18","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much aid her Department has provided to people affected by the crisis in Yemen in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","3074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383926","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Department for International Development works with a range of suppliers to deliver malaria prevention, treatment and research projects. Detailed information on international development projects funded by the UK Government is available on the Development Tracker website.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-06-25T16:35:12.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383926/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383926/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-18","Malaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what consultancy firms her Department works with in the delivery of projects for (a) treatment of and (b) research on malaria.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","3062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383927","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-24","<p>HM Courts and Tribunals Service is improving its enforcement functions. Progress is being made on various issues, including improving the effectiveness of bailiff evictions, improving communications during bailiff proceedings, and standardising how bailiff teams operate.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-06-24T14:37:08.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383927/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383927/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-18","Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what changes have been or are to be made to how bailiffs operate as a result of HM Courts and Tribunals Service recent review of enforcement methods.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","3073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383928","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-26","<p /> <p>The Ministry of Justice (MoJ) estate is a combination of freehold and leasehold premises of which more than 500 properties are held on a leasehold basis. This includes leases from local authorities, police authorities, private sector companies and property management companies. Information relating solely to private sector landlords could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the Government Central Civil Estate, such as the address and whether the property is held on a leasehold/licence basis are recorded on the Central Government property database, Epims. These records are available via the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.data.gov.uk/dataset/epims" target="_blank">www.data.gov.uk/dataset/epims</a></p><p> </p><p>The MoJ is constantly seeking ways of reducing its rental liability. It has secured these reductions both via an active programme of estate rationalisation and ensuring that when lease rent reviews occur these are vigorously contested and nil or minimal increases are agreed.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-26T14:07:57.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383928/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383928/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-18","Ministry of Justice: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which buildings occupied by his Department are owned or part-owned privately; what the total value is of the rent paid to private landlords for the use of such buildings for official duties; and to whom such rent is paid.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383929","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-26","<p>The Public Defender Service (PDS) delivers services within the criminal defence market from advice and representation at the police station and magistrates courts through to advocacy in the higher courts.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-06-26T13:42:30.47Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383929/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383929/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383929/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-18","Public Defender Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his plans are for the role of the Public Defender Service; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","3140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383930","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-24","<p>The information requested is not held centrally in this form and could only be collected at disproportionate cost.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-24T13:49:31.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383930/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383930/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-18","Ministry of Justice: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department spent on (a) external legal advice from Queen's Counsel and (b) other external legal advice between 7 May 2010 and the present day; what the 20 highest amounts paid for external legal advice by his Department were in (i) 2010, (ii) 2011 and (iii) 2012; to whom such payments were made; for what reasons such legal advice was sought; and what the highest day rate paid for external legal advice by his Department was since 7 May 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","3158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383931","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Department is committed to disposing of surplus property assets expeditiously and reducing holding costs. As of 4 September 2015 a total of 80 courts closed under the Court Estate Reform Programme have been sold attracting disposal receipts of £49.18m.</p><p> </p><p>The total cumulative gross benefits expected from the 2010 Court Estate Reform Programme are £152m, consisting of resource savings from court closures of £98m and gross capital proceeds of £54m from the sale of buildings.</p><p> </p><p>The disposal of surplus property assets is dependent on a number of factors, such as the market, potential future use, location and the fact that some are occupied in part by the police and local authorities which also make disposal difficult. Five of the closed court buildings which have not been disposed of are either under offer or on the market. Of those which have not yet been brought to the market, four court buildings have shared locations with the police which means the future of the building is tied in with the Police Station, one has a flying freehold issue and the other three were closed recently. We are working on bringing all of them to the market as soon as possible.</p><p>There are temporary costs associated with making sure unused buildings are kept secure, protecting the fabric of the building and property rates payable to local councils. In addition, decommissioning the buildings to make them ready for sale results in some costs which cannot be disaggregated from the overall running costs. However, these are significantly lower than the costs of running the courts when open, which will have included estates costs, staffing costs and the cost of the judiciary. On average the estates running costs alone for these courts are now more than £4,000 lower per month, almost £50,000 less a year, than when the courts were open. That does not include the further substantial savings from staffing and judiciary costs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Table: Monthly cost of each court building which has been closed since May 2010 but not yet disposed of as at 4 September 2015</strong></p><p> </p><table><thead><tr><td><p><strong>Court building</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average monthly cost<sup>1, </sup></strong><sup>5</sup></p></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><p>Alton Magistrates’ Court<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>£9,828</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bracknell Magistrates’ Court</p></td><td><p>£5,319</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cirencester Magistrates’ Court</p></td><td><p>£1,472</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Coleford Magistrates’ Court</p></td><td><p>£1,561</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Keighley Magistrates’ Court (sitting at Bingley)</p></td><td><p>£2,011</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Knutsford Crown Court<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>£9,274</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Liverpool Magistrates’ Court<sup>4</sup></p></td><td><p>Not available</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lyndhurst Magistrates’ Court</p></td><td><p>£1,783</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oswestry Magistrates’ Court / County Court</p></td><td><p>£2,269</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pontefract Magistrates’ Court</p></td><td><p>£1,957</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Spalding Magistrates’ Court<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>£3,909</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Totnes Magistrates’ Court<sup>3</sup></p></td><td><p>£790</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Towcester Magistrates’ Court<sup>3</sup></p></td><td><p>£445</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Footnotes:</strong></p><p>1. Monthly cost based on financial year data 2014/15 (unless otherwise stated). Holding costs include rates, fuel and utilities, facilities management, telephony and other property costs.</p><p>2. These courts closed in financial year 2014/15 and the stated average monthly cost is therefore based on the last three months of 2014/15. The stated costs for these 3 courts are abnormally high because maintenance costs are likely to include decommissioning costs which are incurred shortly after closure. It is not possible to strip out any decommissioning costs from this answer without incurring disproportionate costs.</p><p>3. Monthly cost based on financial year data 2013/14 and 2014/15 in order to address accounting adjustments made in 2014/15.</p><p>4. Liverpool (Dale Street) Magistrates' Court was integrated into the QEII Law Courts as of 30 June, creating a single centre for crime in the city of Liverpool.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-09-14T13:25:11.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383931/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383931/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-18","Courts: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the monthly running cost is of each court building which has been closed but not disposed of since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","3159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383932","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-09","<p>Since 7 May 2015, there has only been 1 voluntary redundancy where the individual has left the Ministry of Justice. One further offer has been made and an outcome is awaited.</p><p> </p><p>The number of staff that actually took an Exit by either Compulsory Redundancy or ‘Other Exit’ including Voluntary Redundancy within the Ministry of Justice including its Executive Agencies is published each year within the ‘Ministry of Justice Annual Report and Accounts’.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent ‘Annual Report and Accounts’ covering 2014-15 can be found at: <a title="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/434016/moj-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-15.pdf" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/434016/moj-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-15.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/434016/moj-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-15.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Accounts for 2015/16 will be published in the usual way during June 2016, which will include the numbers of actual redundancies during this period.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-07-09T09:16:06.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383932/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383932/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-18","Ministry of Justice: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many employees in his Department have been (a) made redundant or (b) offered redundancy since 7 May 2015.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","3156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383933","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-23","<p>Improving the use of digital technology is key to modernising our justice system in England and Wales. We are reforming the Criminal Justice System to reduce reliance on paper both in the administration of our courts, and in the courtroom.</p><p>Our HMCTS Reform Programme will build on this foundation and ensure that the justice system makes better use of technology to provide easier access to a more responsive and swifter system.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-23T15:36:50.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383933/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383933/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-18","Courts: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress he has made on plans for paperless working in the courts.","false","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","3249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383934","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-06-24","<p>The Northern Ireland Office leases office space from HM Treasury in 1 Horse Guards Road, London. This building is on a PFI contract. However, my Department pays its leasing charges to HM Treasury and not to a private landlord.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-06-24T14:20:21.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383934/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383934/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-18","Northern Ireland Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, which buildings occupied by her Department are owned or part-owned privately; what the total value is of the rent paid to private landlords for the use of such buildings for official duties; and to whom such rent is paid.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383935","Scotland Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Scotland Office’s premises in Edinburgh are privately owned. The building is shared with several other government bodies which contribute towards its cost under civil estate occupancy agreements. The total annual value of the rent in 2015-16, including for space paid for by other government bodies, is £93,060. The rent is paid to Ruthven Properties Ltd.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-06-25T14:07:00.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383935/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383935/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383935/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-18","Scotland Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, which buildings occupied by his Department are owned or part-owned privately; what the total value is of the rent paid to private landlords for the use of such buildings for official duties; and to whom such rent is paid.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383936","Scotland Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>All running cost expenditure in the Scotland Office is subject to rigorous control. The Office’s plans for spending in years after the current financial year will be agreed with HM Treasury in the light of the department’s settlements.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-06-25T14:09:35.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383936/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383936/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-18","Scotland Office: Operating Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what steps he plans to take to reduce his Department's running costs between 2015 and 2020; and what savings he plans to make from reducing his Department's running costs in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","3128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383937","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2015-06-23","<p>The data matching of electors as part of the transition to Individual Electoral Registration took place in summer 2014 in England and Wales and following the referendum on independence in Scotland. In addition to sending the information to Honourable Members, the Commission published the number and percentage of electors matched within local authority areas on its website.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0007/177964/CLR-Data-LA-results-WEBSITE.xlsx" target="_blank">http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0007/177964/CLR-Data-LA-results-WEBSITE.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0020/179030/CLR-Scotland-LA-Data-WEBSITE.xlsx" target="_blank">http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0020/179030/CLR-Scotland-LA-Data-WEBSITE.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>The Commission has more recently reported on how many of the entries on the May 2015 electoral registers do not relate to individually registered electors – those who were not data matched and have also not subsequently made an individual application to register. This data was also sent to Honourable Members and was published on the Commission’s website.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0007/190465/IER-May-2015-electoral-registers-data.xlsx" target="_blank">http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0007/190465/IER-May-2015-electoral-registers-data.xlsx</a></p><p> </p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2015-06-23T10:45:31.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383937/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383937/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2015-06-18","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, what proportion of electors in each local authority area are data matched.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","3246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383938","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-26","<p>No accessibility funding has been made available directly to Transport for Greater Manchester (TfGM), but since 2006 almost £12.5m has been allocated under the Access for All programme to provide step free access to seven stations in the TfGM area. A further two stations were added to the programme last year to be delivered before 2019. I would be happy to meet the Honourable Member for Denton and Reddish to discuss Reddish North station.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-26T11:14:55.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383938/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383938/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Railway Stations: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what resources he (a) has made and (b) plans to make available to Transport for Greater Manchester to make the county's railway stations fully accessible for wheelchair users; and if he will meet the hon. Member for Denton and Reddish to discuss resources for wheelchair accessibility at Reddish North station.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383939","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-23","<p>The number of reported personal injury road accidents by severity on M56 between junctions 12 and 14 for the last three years is given in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong>Number of reported personal injury accidents on M56 between junctions 12 - 14: 2011 - 2013</strong></p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td colspan="3"><p>Number of accidents</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td> </td><td><p>Fatal</p></td><td><p>Serious</p></td><td><p>Slight</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td> </td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td> </td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td> </td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>22</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>Data for 2014 will be available on 26<sup>th</sup> June 2015 when it is first published. Damage only accidents are not collected by the Department.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-23T13:57:38.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383939/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383939/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","M56: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many road traffic accidents have happened on the M56 between junctions 12 and 14 in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383940","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-26","<p>Scottish Ministers have substantial executively devolved powers in relation to the railways in Scotland. This allows them to determine matters such as the level of service and fares policy.　 In addition, Scottish Ministers have executive powers over rail infrastructure, including the responsibility for specifying and funding the outputs they wish Network Rail to deliver in Scotland. Improvements to the Far North Line are therefore a matter for the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-26T11:19:59.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383940/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383940/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Far North Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to support Network Rail achieve and sustain journey time reductions on the Far North Rail Line from Inverness to Thurso and Wick; and if he will make increased funding available to the Scottish Government for investment in that line.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","3214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383941","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-25","<p>In 2014, Glasgow airport provided connectivity to 69 destinations with at least a weekly service (i.e. at least 52 direct passenger flight departures, domestic and international). Whilst London City provided connections to 43 destinations, Heathrow 169 and Gatwick 189.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-25T13:52:38.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383941/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383941/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383941/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Glasgow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how the connectivity of Glasgow Airport compares to that of (a) London City, (b) Heathrow and (c) Gatwick airports.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","3222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383942","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-26","<p>The Government’s Community Rail Development Strategy looks at innovative ways of operating local rural branch lines, through a programme of cost management, a drive to increase passenger numbers and direct community involvement via local authorities, community rail partnerships, and other stakeholder groups.</p><p>The bulk of Government support for local and rural rail comes via the franchising process and direct support for the rail industry, which allow for the continuation or improvement of passenger services on many local and rural railways for the benefit of all users. As all non-regulated fares are set on a commercial level by the operator, they can choose to offer promotional fares and other incentives should they wish. In addition, we have capped regulated fares at the level of the Retail Price Index (RPI) for two years running, and will continue to do so for the life of this parliament.</p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>The Club 50 scheme is a ScotRail initiative, which will offer discounted travel and other benefits, including from other partners, specifically for the over 50s. As the ScotRail franchise is specified, let and managed by the Scottish Ministers under the devolved powers relating to railways in Scotland, funding issues are a matter for the Scottish Government.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-26T11:23:54.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383942/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383942/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383942/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Railways: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to encourage greater use of rural rail lines by those over 50 years of age; and if he will provide increased funding to the Scottish Government to encourage uptake of the Club 50 scheme.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","3215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383943","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-25","<p>We have been concerned about the direct and indirect impact of improvement works, poor performance and asset reliability on passengers; at times the delays and disruption for passengers have been inexcusable.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>One of the key priorities in this new Parliament is to see train performance in the South-East improve.　Officials and I have been working closely with the Chief Executive of Network Rail, Mark Carne, and the Management team of Southern and GTR to understand the causes of the problems and the plans to solve the issue.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>I have also been chairing weekly meetings with senior members of Network Rail, GTR and Southern to ensure progress is being made.　 Passengers are at the heart of these discussions; in particular the need for better communication with passengers. We are committed to see improvements in this area, as well as improvements to performance.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-25T14:55:30.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383943/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383943/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to investigate the management and communications with customers of (a) Southern and (b) Network Rail.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","3132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383944","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-25","<p>As an EU Regulation the United Kingdom is obliged to implement such measures as specified. The requirements under Regulation 1071/2009 were met by amending domestic legislation which was implemented on 4 December 2011. These legislative changes will be the subject of a Post Implementation Review in 2016.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-25T10:01:30.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383944/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383944/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Large Goods Vehicles: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his policy is on the application of Regulation EC 1071/2009 concerning occupation of transport operators.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Meale","Mansfield","Sir Alan Meale","3124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383945","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-25","<p>On 30<sup>th</sup> April 2015, the Department for Transport received a formal notice of infraction from the European Commission concerning the UK’s application of Regulation (EC) no 1071/2009 (on access to the occupation of road transport operator). We will consider the content of this letter and respond within two months, in line with Article 258 of the Treaty of the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As this is a live case, and communications with the European Commission concerning infractions are in most cases confidential, it would not be appropriate to publish our response.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>At this stage, no decisions have been made about any actions the UK may take in the light of the issues raised by the Commission.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-25T10:07:36.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383945/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383945/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Large Goods Vehicles: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish his Department's response to the formal notification of infraction from the European Commission concerning the Government's application of Regulation EC 1071/2009 on access to the occupation of a road transport operator; and what steps he plans to take in response to that notification.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Meale","Mansfield","Sir Alan Meale","3125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383946","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-25","<p>As part of the Government’s Transparency Agenda information about Department for Transport properties is published on the data.gov.uk website. Information on the properties owned and leased by the Department is available via the following web link:</p><p><a href="http://data.gov.uk/dataset/epims" target="_blank">http://data.gov.uk/dataset/epims</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>The specific information requested on rental payments is not centrally recorded and could only be provided at disproportionate costs.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-25T13:47:31.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383946/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383946/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Department for Transport: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which buildings occupied by his Department are owned or part-owned privately; what the total value is of the rent paid to private landlords for the use of such buildings for official duties; and to whom such rent is paid.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383947","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-23","<p>We expect to receive final proposals from First Great Western and to make a decision over the summer.　 We do not anticipate that the proposals will require a Section 54 undertaking or designation as a franchise asset.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-23T13:16:04.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383947/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383947/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383947/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","First Great Western","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects to make a decision on whether to grant First Great Western permission to order new trains to operate on its intercity routes to Devon and Cornwall; and whether he expects that permission will require a section 54 undertaking of the designation of such trains, or their lease agreement as a franchise asset.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","3081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383948","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-23","<p>Both my Ministerial colleagues and I, as well as Departmental officials, regularly hold meetings to discuss Network Rail operations. These can also involve interested external organisations.</p><p> </p>","Derbyshire Dales","Mr Patrick McLoughlin",,"2015-06-23T13:20:21.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383948/answer","Biography information for Sir Patrick McLoughlin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383948/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 17 June 2015 to Question 2371, what meetings (a) he, (b) other Ministers in his Department and (c) officials in his Department have held to discuss Network Rail since 1 March 2015; when each such meeting took place; and which organisations external to the core Department were present at each such meeting.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","3117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383949","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-23","<p>The department sponsors the rail industry’s FutureRailway programme which supports research, development and demonstration of innovative rail solutions. Recent FutureRailway initiatives, which have secured widespread interest and engagement from UK based suppliers, include a £4.5m competition to develop more energy efficient, self-powered trains and a successful trial of a battery powered train.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport is also working with the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills and the Rail Supply Group to strengthen the UK rail supply chain – including the manufacture of rolling stock - so that it is better able to win work here and abroad.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-23T13:00:07.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383949/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383949/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Rolling Stock: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he has taken to encourage research and development into the production of new diesel multiple units by UK-based manufacturers.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","3080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383950","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-25","<p>In setting the Airports Commission’s terms of reference, the Government asked it to consider the UK’s future requirements for international and domestic connectivity. We will carefully consider the Airports Commissions final report and its recommendations when the final report is published.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-25T14:05:05.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383950/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383950/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Airports: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effects of each of the shortlisted options for a new runway in South East England on connectivity to Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","3051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383951","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-23","<p>Detailed decisions around staff training and capability rightly sits with the train operators.　 In recent competitions (see the Northern and TransPennine Invitations To Tender for the most recent examples) we have put additional requirements on bidders to work with staff to build capability and skills, encouraging train operators to think about these vital matters.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The rail industry is developing a comprehensive skills strategy identifying the key challenges facing the sector and focussing on those areas that will support growth and productivity.　 This work has the support of my department, the Rail Delivery Group and the Rail Supply Group and will be co-ordinated by the National Skills Academy for Railway Engineering.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-23T11:40:27.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383951/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383951/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-18","Train Operating Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to include provisions on improving the quality of and access to training and continuing professional development for employeers of train operating companies in all future franchise agreements.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","3072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383952","Wales Office","false","2015-06-23","<p>The Wales Office occupies two buildings; one in London and the other in Cardiff. The London building is owned by the Department, and we lease part of a privately owned building in Cardiff at a rental cost of £89,958 per annum. The rent for the Cardiff building is paid to Colliers International, the managing agents for the landlord.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2015-06-23T11:56:59.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383952/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383952/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-06-18","Wales Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, which buildings occupied by his Department are owned or part-owned privately; what the total value is of the rent paid to private landlords for the use of such buildings for official duties; and to whom such rent is paid.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383953","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The Department for Work and Pensions occupies the majority of its estate under a Private Finance Initiative (PFI) known as the PRIME Contract.</p><p> </p><p>Under this PFI, the Department does not own any of the Estate we occupy, but leases back fully serviced accommodation from its private sector partner, Telereal Trillium. The Department pays an all-inclusive unitary price for the space occupied which includes the total cost of the rent and thirteen Facilities Management services, such as cleaning, security and all lifecycle and reactive maintenance and repairs.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-24T14:02:25.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383953/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383953/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which buildings occupied by his Department are owned or part-owned privately; what the total value is of the rent paid to private landlords for the use of such buildings for official duties; and to whom such rent is paid.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383954","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The available information for the number of Sanction appeals and reconsiderations overturned, in respect of Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance, is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>:</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-24T12:59:50.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383954/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383954/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits: Renfrewshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefit claimants in Renfrewshire that appealed all or part of a sanction of their benefit were successful in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","3089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383955","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p>Information that is available in respect of Jobseeker’s Allowance (JSA) lone parent sanctions is published and available at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>:</p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p><p>The rest of the information as requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-24T12:35:37.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383955/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383955/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits: Renfrewshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many sanctions were given to benefit claimants in Renfrewshire who are (a) lone parents and (b) have a learning disability in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","3090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383956","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-23","<p /> <p>Stat-Xplore forms part of the package which is used within the Department when publishing Official Statistics. It is used in conjunction with a Statistical First Release and set of summary statistical tables, with Stat-Xplore allowing users to construct their own bespoke statistical tables at very detailed level.</p><p>Stat-Xplore was updated in May 2015 to include new features and improvements, based on feedback from users.</p><p> </p><p>A comprehensive user guide is available within the Stat-Xplore system which guides users through all the features of Stat-Xplore. In addition, a dedicated Stat-Xplore e-mail address allows users to send queries or requests for help in relation to Stat-Xplore.</p><p> </p><p>Over 3,100 people have registered to use Stat-Xplore, and over 40,000 tables have been produced and downloaded by users since Stat-Xplore was launched in April 2013.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-23T15:24:41.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383956/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383956/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Department for Work and Pensions: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the usability of the Stat-Xplore website.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","3115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383957","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The Qualifying Week for Winter Fuel Payment assessments is set at the third week of September to ensure that the maximum number of payments (over 95 per cent of eligible cases) are made automatically before Christmas, typically the coldest part of winter. Those that are not paid automatically are accepted as clerical claims up to the 31 March, and payment is issued as soon as possible. There are no plans to review the Qualifying Week.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-24T13:57:08.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383957/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383957/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Winter Fuel Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to make payments of winter fuel allowance to those who qualify for such payments after the third Monday in September and before 1 January before the end of the same financial year.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Meale","Mansfield","Sir Alan Meale","3123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383958","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-23","<p /> <p>The information requested is not available. The Work Capability Assessment assesses claimants for Employment and Support Allowance against a number of descriptors covering physical, mental, cognitive and intellectual functions.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-23T14:21:14.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383958/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383958/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will estimate the number of claimants receiving benefits pertaining to a mental health condition who have been given an assessment of whether they are fit to work based only on their physical health.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","3126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383959","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-23","<p /> <p>The Government does not produce child poverty statistics at a local authority level.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-23T11:48:21.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383959/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383959/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the number of children in the borough of Walsall living in poverty in (a) households including a person who is in employment and (b) other households.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","3076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383960","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The Department has a range of GB-wide, “extra costs” benefits intended to provide a contribution towards the extra costs faced by people with long-term health conditions and disabilities. Attendance Allowance (AA) is available to those who have long term care or supervision needs that arise from age 65 onwards; and Disability Living Allowance (DLA) or Personal Independence Payment (PIP) to those who develop care, daily living or mobility needs prior to age 65. Where the entitlement conditions for DLA or PIP continue to be met after age 65 these benefits can continue to be paid.</p><p> </p><p>Executive and legislative competence for these benefits will be devolved to Scotland once the Scotland Bill currently passing through Parliament receives Royal Assent and the powers are commenced.</p><p>The Department is committed to encouraging older people to take up the benefits they are entitled to and uses a range of channels to communicate with claimants and advisers ‒ including leaflets, and the government information website GOV.UK: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/browse/benefits/disability" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/browse/benefits/disability</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-24T13:44:45.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383960/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383960/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure that older people with disabilities are adequately supported to meet their higher costs through nationally-administered disability benefits.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","3049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383961","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given on the 2 March 2015 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-02-23/225001/" target="_blank">UIN 225001</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-24T13:15:17.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383961/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383961/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of how much benefit has been withheld from claimants as a result of sanctions in each quarter since 2005.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","3238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383962","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-23","<p /> <p>The Department asks Local authorities to supply details of their use of Discretionary Housing Payments on a 6 monthly basis. Data for 2013/14 is provided at the link below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/discretionary-housing-payments-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/discretionary-housing-payments-statistics</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-23T14:08:46.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383962/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383962/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Housing Benefit: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much has been awarded in discretionary housing payments by each local authority in London (a) in total, (b) to people affected by the household benefit cap, (c) to people affected by a reduction in local housing allowance rates and (d) to people affected by the under-occupancy penalty.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383963","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The Department does not monitor the use of food banks and has no plans to do so.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-24T12:20:14.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383963/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383963/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Food Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will take steps to compile data on the number of people using food banks.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383964","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p>DWP has made a number of operational improvements in benefit processes, supporting both speed of clearance and overall customer experience.</p><p> </p><p>There are no delays. In fact, processing speeds have improved, steadily increasing from 85.8% of JSA claims processed in 16 days in 2009-10 to 96% in 2004-15. We have also steadily increased the number of Employment and Support Allowance claims processed in 16 days from 72.9% in 2009-10 to 93.6% in 2014-15.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-24T12:29:44.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383964/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383964/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to reduce delays in benefits payments.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383965","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-29","<p>The number of families receiving child tax credits depends on a series of assumptions including earnings and employment growth.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A recent IFS publication suggested that returning the per-child element of child tax credit to its real (CPI-adjusted) 2003-04 level would reduce entitlements for about 3.7 million low-income families with children by an average of £1,400 per year, and would cut spending by about £5bn.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","3242","2015-06-29T13:43:31.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383965/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383965/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-18","Child Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he will estimate the effect on the annual income of the (a) poorest 10 per cent, (b) poorest 20 per cent, (c) poorest 25 per cent, (d) poorest 30 per cent, (e) richest 40 per cent, (f) richest 30 per cent, (g) richest 25 per cent, (h) richest 20 per cent and (i) richest 10 per cent of households if the child element of child tax credit was reduced to 2003-04 levels in real terms.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383966","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-30","<p /> <p>The national roll out of Universal Credit is on track. Torbay is part of our Tranche 4 roll out schedule which runs from December 2015 to April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>I enclose a link to overall roll out and expansion plans:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/414937/universal-credit-national-expansion-tranche-three-and-four.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/414937/universal-credit-national-expansion-tranche-three-and-four.pdf</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-30T14:02:16.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383966/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383966/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Universal Credit: Torbay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to further roll out the Universal Credit programme in Torbay constituency in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Kevin Foster","Torbay","Kevin Foster","3273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383967","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-23","<p /> <p>The information is not available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-23T14:04:17.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383967/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383967/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people affected by the household benefit cap who were placed by the local authority in temporary accommodation were placed outside their local authority area in (a) 2013, (b) 2014 and (c) 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383968","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-25","<p /> <p>DWP commissions a wide range of policy research and evaluation through its Social and Economic Research Framework, made up of more than 50 research organisations and academic institutions, including IFS, which we contract to carry out specific pieces of research. Such contracts are in the public domain and our protocol is that all research reports are published.</p><p> </p><p>Some examples of contracts which we have had with IFS during the past five years include:</p><p> </p><p>· DWP ad hoc research report number 11 ‘Benefit Cap: Analysis of outcomes of capped claimants’ where DWP carried out the original work and we commissioned IFS to conduct an independent peer review;</p><p>· Our annual statistical publication on Households Below Average Income, which is quality assured by IFS</p><p>· DWP report 606, ‘The lone parent pilots 24-36 months: the final impact assessment’</p><p> </p><p>It is important to note that, apart from payments in respect of contracts for specific pieces of research, we do not provide any other funding to IFS.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-25T14:26:20.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383968/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383968/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Department for Work and Pensions: Institute for Fiscal Studies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department made any payments to the Institute of Fiscal Studies in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mhairi Black","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Ms Mhairi Black","3139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383969","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>As part of an initial discussion customers claiming Jobseekers Allowance have an interview with a Work Coach. The purpose of this is to fully explain and agree the Claimant Commitment.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-24T13:19:40.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383969/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383969/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure that all benefit claimants understand the Claimant Commitment.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","3141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383970","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-23","<p /> <p>The available information on average (median) waiting times, at a national level, has been published and is available from the Personal Independence Payment statistics home page: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is assessing the quality of the clearance time data at lower geographical levels and is considering the future release of such information into the public domain. These statistics will be published when they are ready, with the release pre-announced in line with United Kingdom Statistics Authority release protocols.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-23T15:10:31.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383970/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383970/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Personal Independence Payment: Renfrewshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what average length of time applicants in Renfrewshire have waited for personal independence payment assessments since the start of their rollout.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","3137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383971","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-23","<p /> <p>The information available for the number and reason for referral, in respect of Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance sanction decisions, by Jobcentre Plus, is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>:</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-23T14:11:13.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383971/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383971/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what sanctions have been issued by each Jobcentre Plus in each month in 2014.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383972","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The number of households that were subject to the benefit cap in February 2015, the latest available information, in London was 10,520. Data on the number of people placed by their local authority in temporary accommodation is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-24T14:06:11.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383972/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383972/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in London are affected by the household benefit cap; and how many such people have been placed by their local authority in temporary accommodation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383973","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The Government will provide costings for all new policies at the next Budget.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-24T13:10:34.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383973/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383973/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what savings he expects to accrue to the public purse as a result of freezing working-age benefits in (a) 2016-17 and (b) 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","3268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383974","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-23","<p /> <p>It is not possible to provide estimates around a scenario that does not reflect current policy or plans.</p><p> </p><p>Once fully rolled out Universal Credit will mean around 3.2 million households will be better off by an average of £178 a month.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-23T11:40:07.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383974/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383974/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Child Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he will estimate how many people who would otherwise be eligible for universal credit who would not be so eligible if the child element was reduced in real terms to the 2003-04 level of the child element of child tax credit.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383975","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-23","<p /> <p>The trial commenced on 20 April 2015 and therefore it is too early to make an assessment at this stage.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-23T11:42:40.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383975/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383975/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the pilot schemes aimed at in-work claimants.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","3192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383976","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-29","<p>The number of families receiving child tax credits depends on a series of assumptions including earnings and employment growth.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A recent IFS publication suggested that returning the per-child element of child tax credit to its real (CPI-adjusted) 2003-04 level would reduce entitlements for about 3.7 million low-income families with children by an average of £1,400 per year, and would cut spending by about £5bn.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","3224","2015-06-29T13:43:31.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383976/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383976/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-18","Child Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he will estimate the number of people who would no longer receive child tax credits if the child element was reduced to its 2003-04 level in real terms.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383977","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-23","<p /> <p>The latest available information on sanctions, up to December 2014, is published at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>:</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-23T11:52:30.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383977/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383977/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits: East Lothian","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people had their benefits sanctioned in East Lothian in each of the last 12 quarters for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for George Kerevan","East Lothian","George Kerevan","3190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383978","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The information available for the number of Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance sanction decisions by geography is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>:</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-24T13:35:57.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383978/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383978/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefit sanctions in Scotland there were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","3269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383979","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-23","<p /> <p>Local Jobcentre Plus managers have the freedom to develop partnerships with a wide range of organisations based on local needs and circumstances.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-23T11:32:45.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383979/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/383979/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-18","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the feasibility of seconding Job Centre staff to do outreach sessions at food banks to support people who are experiencing problems with the administration of the welfare system.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","3248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381699","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-30","<p>My Department is working to prepare the legislation necessary to create the new legal status of guardian of the property and affairs of a missing person. We are grateful for the continued assistance in this work of the charity, Missing People, and its pro bono lawyers, Clifford Chance. We will bring forward legislation when Parliamentary time allows.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-06-30T15:40:34.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381699/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381699/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-17","Missing Persons","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will decide the timetabling of the legislation proposed in their recent response to their consultation on the guardianship of the property and affairs of missing persons.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hamwee",,"Baroness Hamwee","HL552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381700","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>Following the introduction of Individual Electoral Registration (IER) in Great Britain in 2014, the annual canvass of households has been retained. There are no current plans to exercise an order under Part 1, Section 7(2)(b) of the Electoral Registration and Administration Act 2013.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-06-25T17:04:18.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381700/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381700/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-17","Electoral Register","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to end the requirement for Electoral Registration Officers to canvas households annually.","false","Biography information for Lord Falconer of Thoroton",,"Lord Falconer of Thoroton","HL553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381701","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>We are building a justice system which is simpler, swifter and more efficient. Our estate is a major asset, and in an increasingly digital world, we are looking at how we use our buildings to deliver the best possible service to our users now and in the future. Any new proposals on the future of courts will be subject to consultation.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-07-01T14:17:50.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381701/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381701/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-17","Courts: Closures","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to close courts.","false","Biography information for Lord Falconer of Thoroton",,"Lord Falconer of Thoroton","HL554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381702","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>The Government currently has no plans to publish a white paper on reform of the magistracy. We have yet to see the full impact of changes brought about by our rehabilitation reforms, the Transforming Summary Justice Programme and the new Single Justice Procedure. These are already changing the way that magistrates work. My Rt Hon Friend the Lord Chancellor gave a speech outlining this Government’s approach to criminal justice on 23 June. The content of that speech, “<em>What does a one nation justice policy look like</em>”, can be viewed online at <a title="blocked::https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/what-does-a-one-nation-justice-policy-look-like" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/what-does-a-one-nation-justice-policy-look-like" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/what-does-a-one-nation-justice-policy-look-like</a></p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-07-01T17:05:38.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381702/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381702/answer","What does a one nation justice policy look like - Gove Speech.pdf","What does a one nation justice policy look like - Gove Speech.pdf","Speech - Michael Gove","Speech - Michael Gove","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381702/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-17","Magistrates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to publish a white paper on reform of the magistracy; and if so, when.","false","Biography information for Lord Falconer of Thoroton",,"Lord Falconer of Thoroton","HL555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381703","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-01","<p>There is no specific allocation of Honours for Professors who compete with other candidates in the normal way.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-07-01T15:52:44.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381703/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381703/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-17","Honours","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Wallace of Saltaire on 27 November 2014 (HL2967), whether the reduction in the number of persons styled professor in the list of knighthoods and damehoods in the Queen's Birthday Honours List for 2015 anticipates the next Quinquennial review.","false","Biography information for Lord Jopling",,"Lord Jopling","HL556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381704","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-29","<p>The target timetable for the whole rights of way reforms package to be brought into effect is April 2016.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-06-29T14:43:36.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381704/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381704/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-17","Rights of Way","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 15 June (HL171), when they expect to put in place the secondary legislation and guidance needed to make the relevant provisions concerning footpaths and bridleways.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381705","Department for Education","false","2015-06-29","<p>The department does not hold data on the percentage of primary teachers professionally trained through recognised three-year teacher training courses or one-year postgraduate courses. The department does hold information on primary trainee teachers who were awarded qualified teacher status (QTS).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In the 2012 to 2013 academic year, 28% of those awarded QTS in England trained through an undergraduate programme. 72% trained through a postgraduate programme. This has changed from 37% and 63% respectively in the 2004 to 2005 academic year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Undergraduate courses are typically three or four years. Postgraduate courses are typically for one year and the vast major lead to PGCE.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>Number of primary trainees gaining QTS who were on undergraduate courses</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of primary trainees gaining QTS who were on postgraduate courses </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total number of primary trainees gaining QTS </strong></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Percentage primary trainees gaining QTS who were on undergraduate courses</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Percentage of primary trainees gaining QTS who were on postgraduate courses </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2004/05</strong></p></td><td><p>4,550</p></td><td><p>7,774</p></td><td><p>12,324</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>37%</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>63%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2005/06</strong></p></td><td><p>4,652</p></td><td><p>7,542</p></td><td><p>12,194</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>38%</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>62%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2006/07</strong></p></td><td><p>5,091</p></td><td><p>7,397</p></td><td><p>12,488</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>41%</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>59%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2007/08</strong></p></td><td><p>5,335</p></td><td><p>7,916</p></td><td><p>13,251</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>40%</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>60%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2008/09</strong></p></td><td><p>5,609</p></td><td><p>10,135</p></td><td><p>15,744</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>36%</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>64%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p>5,212</p></td><td><p>10,454</p></td><td><p>15,666</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>33%</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>67%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p>5,093</p></td><td><p>10,701</p></td><td><p>15,794</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>32%</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>68%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p>5,381</p></td><td><p>12,101</p></td><td><p>17,482</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>31%</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>69%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p>5,111</p></td><td><p>12,934</p></td><td><p>18,045</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>28%</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>72%</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>1) Data excludes Teach First and Assessment Only</p></td><td colspan="2"><p> </p></td><td colspan="3"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="5"><p>2) Data includes Employment Based Teacher Training (EBITT)</p></td><td colspan="3"><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="5"><p>3) Data for 2013/13 includes School Direct Trainees</p></td><td colspan="3"><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-06-29T11:04:46.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381705/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381705/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-17","Teachers: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of primary school teachers in England have been professionally trained through recognised three-year teacher training courses, and what percentage through a one-year Postgraduate Course in Education; and how those percentages have changed since 2005.","false","Biography information for Lord Maginnis of Drumglass",,"Lord Maginnis of Drumglass","HL558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381706","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-08","<p>The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) does not commission accredited programmes exclusively for Indeterminate Sentence Prisoners. Programme and public protection resources are allocated based on offenders' type, level of risk and criminogenic needs in order to maximise public safety and value for money.</p><p>It is important that Indeterminate Sentence Prisoners have access to services that are appropriate to their risk and needs. NOMS has been using an evidence based approach to move investment in interventions to higher intensity longer programmes that are more likely to meet the complex needs of Indeterminate Sentence Prisoners. This approach increases the availability and access to these services across the estate.</p><p>HMP Durham, like many other local prisons, has not been commissioned to deliver accredited programmes as the primary function of the prison is to serve the courts and hold prisoners who are on remand. Where a prisoner is identified as having a need for a specific accredited programme, and has sufficient time left in their sentence to complete the programme in custody (including prisoners who are serving indefinite sentences for public protection), they would be transferred to an appropriate prison delivering the identified programme.</p><p>HMP Acklington is the former name of HMP Northumberland. HMP Northumberland was formed following the merger of two separate prisons – HMP Acklington and HMP Castington on 31 October 2011<strong>.</strong></p><p>HMP Northumberland is commissioned to deliver two different accredited programmes. Thinking Skills Programme (TSP) which is a short non offence specific thinking skills programme and Core Sexual Offending Treatment Programme (SOTP) which is designed for medium to high risk sex offenders.</p>There have been no cancellations of courses.<p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-07-08T15:45:32.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381706/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381706/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-17","Prison Sentences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what accredited courses are or have been available to those serving indefinite sentences for public protection in (1) HMP Durham and (2) HMP Acklington; and how many of each have been cancelled in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381707","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>The National Offender Management Service is committed to reducing reoffending by giving prisoners the support they need to break away from a life of crime. An important factor in their rehabilitation is providing them with the opportunity to learn new skills, contribute positively to prison life and develop a strong work ethos. As part of this, prisoners have always carried out tasks under the supervision of staff to assist the running of the prison and to gain skills in preparation for release.</p><p> </p><p>HMP Durham has recently added further opportunities to do this, with jobs such as the receipt and recording of routine applications; the provision of general information; non-confidential prisoner record preparation; the issuing of toiletries, and the delivery of information as part of the induction programme for new prisoners.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMP Acklington merged with HMP Castington in March 2013 to form HMP Northumberland. From December 2013 HMP Northumberland has been operated under contract by Sodexo Justice Services. Since December 2013 prisoners have carried out some tasks previously undertaken by staff related to the stores department, prisoner property area, general cleaning, catering and electrical testing.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-07-01T14:21:40.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381707/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381707/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-17","Prisons","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what tasks, if any, prisoners are now asked to undertake that hitherto were undertaken by staff at (1) HMP Durham, and (2) HMP Acklington.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381708","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>The Government has no plans to change the law to provide further protection for the right of individuals to freedom of expression.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-07-01T15:05:24.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381708/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381708/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-17","Freedom of Expression","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to changing the law to provide further protection for the right of individuals to freedom of expression, in the light of the recent case involving Professor Tim Hunt.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381709","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>Tackling domestic violence is a core priority for this Government. The Government have made a number of changes to the system to make it easier for victims of domestic violence to access legal aid, regardless of gender. The Government have made changes to existing evidence requirements, to make legal aid easier to acquire, and introduced new acceptable forms of evidence.</p><p> </p><p>These changes include Domestic Violence Protection Orders and police bail or a binding over order for a domestic violence offence as acceptable forms of evidence. They have also expanded the definition of ‘health professional’ to include practitioner psychologists. Evidence that someone has been turned away from a refuge because of lack of accommodation will also be accepted.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-07-01T14:19:24.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381709/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381709/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-17","Domestic Violence: Legal Aid Scheme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Bates on 16 June (HL Deb, col 1072) concerning domestic violence, whether male victims of domestic violence will have access to legal aid.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381710","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-25","<p>Between 1 April 2007 and 31 December 2014, 16,473 UK Regular Armed Forces personnel were prescribed mefloquine (commercial name Lariam). Up to 31 March 2015, 1,066 (6 per cent) were assessed as having a mental health disorder at their initial assessment at an MOD Department for Community Mental Health (DCMH) or on admission to an MOD in-patient provider. It is not possible from centrally-held data to identify whether an assessment is associated with a patient having taken mefloquine.</p><p> </p><p>Former Service men and women are treated by the NHS and their status as a veteran is not always recorded on their NHS medical records. It is therefore not possible to say how many former Service personnel have required psychiatric treatment after taking mefloquine.</p><p> </p><p>Between 1 April 2007 and 31 December 2014, 536 UK Armed Forces personnel were prescribed mefloquine prior to or whilst on deployment to Afghanistan. Up to 31 March 2015, 43 (8 per cent) were assessed as having a mental health disorder at their initial assessment at an MOD DCMH or on admission to an MOD in-patient provider.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL564","2015-06-25T15:20:29.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381710/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381710/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-17","Armed Forces: Mefloquine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many (1) serving and (2) former service men and women have required psychiatric treatment after taking Lariam (mefloquine).","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381711","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-25","<p>Between 1 April 2007 and 31 December 2014, 16,473 UK Regular Armed Forces personnel were prescribed mefloquine (commercial name Lariam). Up to 31 March 2015, 1,066 (6 per cent) were assessed as having a mental health disorder at their initial assessment at an MOD Department for Community Mental Health (DCMH) or on admission to an MOD in-patient provider. It is not possible from centrally-held data to identify whether an assessment is associated with a patient having taken mefloquine.</p><p> </p><p>Former Service men and women are treated by the NHS and their status as a veteran is not always recorded on their NHS medical records. It is therefore not possible to say how many former Service personnel have required psychiatric treatment after taking mefloquine.</p><p> </p><p>Between 1 April 2007 and 31 December 2014, 536 UK Armed Forces personnel were prescribed mefloquine prior to or whilst on deployment to Afghanistan. Up to 31 March 2015, 43 (8 per cent) were assessed as having a mental health disorder at their initial assessment at an MOD DCMH or on admission to an MOD in-patient provider.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL563","2015-06-25T15:20:29.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381711/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381711/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-17","Armed Forces: Mefloquine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many service men and women who were deployed to Afghanistan between 2007 and 2014, and were required to take Lariam (mefloquine), subsequently required mental health treatment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381712","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>Lariam (mefloquine), is an extremely effective antimalarial and is one of a number of antimalarials for travellers currently recommended by the Advisory Committee on Malaria Prevention (ACMP), an expert advisory committee of Public Health England (PHE) established in 1998 to formulate evidence-based guidelines on malaria prevention in the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The use of mefloquine, for travellers, including military personnel, to high risk areas should be based on an individual risk assessment that takes into consideration the destination of travel, planned activities while travelling and the individual’s current health and medical history.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The ACMP regularly reviews data on safety and efficacy of all antimalarials. Whenever new evidence about antimalarials appears the ACMP considers this as part of its continuous process of developing advice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The ACMP will be meeting in summer 2015 to finalise the 2015 revision of the ACMP guidelines. This meeting will review current evidence on the use of mefloquine, including data provided by Roche, and recommendations made by other countries including the United States with regard to the use of mefloquine for malaria prevention.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL566 ; HL567","2015-06-30T16:05:46.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381712/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381712/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-17","Mefloquine: Armed Forces","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what advice they have received from Public Health England on Lariam (mefloquine), in particular in relation to members of the armed forces serving in Afghanistan.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381713","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>Lariam (mefloquine), is an extremely effective antimalarial and is one of a number of antimalarials for travellers currently recommended by the Advisory Committee on Malaria Prevention (ACMP), an expert advisory committee of Public Health England (PHE) established in 1998 to formulate evidence-based guidelines on malaria prevention in the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The use of mefloquine, for travellers, including military personnel, to high risk areas should be based on an individual risk assessment that takes into consideration the destination of travel, planned activities while travelling and the individual’s current health and medical history.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The ACMP regularly reviews data on safety and efficacy of all antimalarials. Whenever new evidence about antimalarials appears the ACMP considers this as part of its continuous process of developing advice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The ACMP will be meeting in summer 2015 to finalise the 2015 revision of the ACMP guidelines. This meeting will review current evidence on the use of mefloquine, including data provided by Roche, and recommendations made by other countries including the United States with regard to the use of mefloquine for malaria prevention.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL565 ; HL567","2015-06-30T16:05:46.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381713/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381713/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-17","Mefloquine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the warning issued by Roche, the manufacturer of Lariam (mefloquine), in October 2013 that the drug "may induce potentially serious neuropsychiatric disorders".","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381714","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>Lariam (mefloquine), is an extremely effective antimalarial and is one of a number of antimalarials for travellers currently recommended by the Advisory Committee on Malaria Prevention (ACMP), an expert advisory committee of Public Health England (PHE) established in 1998 to formulate evidence-based guidelines on malaria prevention in the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The use of mefloquine, for travellers, including military personnel, to high risk areas should be based on an individual risk assessment that takes into consideration the destination of travel, planned activities while travelling and the individual’s current health and medical history.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The ACMP regularly reviews data on safety and efficacy of all antimalarials. Whenever new evidence about antimalarials appears the ACMP considers this as part of its continuous process of developing advice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The ACMP will be meeting in summer 2015 to finalise the 2015 revision of the ACMP guidelines. This meeting will review current evidence on the use of mefloquine, including data provided by Roche, and recommendations made by other countries including the United States with regard to the use of mefloquine for malaria prevention.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL565 ; HL566","2015-06-30T16:05:46.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381714/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381714/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-17","Mefloquine: USA","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the decision taken by the United States Special Forces to ban the use of Lariam (mefloquine) for malaria prophylaxis.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381715","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-25","<p>As at 22 June 2015, the Ministry of Defence holds 11,505 packs of mefloquine (commercial name Lariam) each containing eight tablets.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-06-25T15:19:31.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381715/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381715/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-17","Mefloquine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what stocks of Lariam (mefloquine) they currently hold.","false","Biography information for Baroness Corston",,"Baroness Corston","HL568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381716","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-01","<p>The potential impacts of decriminalisation are being considered as part of the TV Licence Fee Enforcement Review. This review is in its final stages and David Perry QC will report his findings to the Secretary of State by the end of June.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-07-01T16:23:09.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381716/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381716/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-17","Television: Licensing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact on public service broadcasting of decriminalising non-payment of the licence fee.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381717","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-01","<p>S4C currently receives funding both from the exchequer (£6.8 million for 2015-16) and £74.5 million from the licence fee, for 2015-16 and also 2016-17, the end of the licence fee settlement. All options around the licence fee will be considered as part of the Charter Review. The level of all exchequer funding for public bodies will be a matter for the Spending Review, which has yet to begin.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-07-01T16:22:44.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381717/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381717/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-17","S4C","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to ensure that funding for S4C does not drop below its current level.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381718","Home Office","false","2015-06-24","<p>EU Member States have obligations requiring them to accept and consider without delay an application for asylum from any migrant arriving on their territory. These obligations include the application of the Dublin Regulation to determine which EU member State is responsible for examining the merits of the application. Her Majesty's Government has made very clear that it expects all EU Member States to honour those obligations as we do.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-06-24T13:51:42.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381718/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381718/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-17","Refugees: Mediterranean Sea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what efforts they have made to ensure that refugees crossing the Mediterranean are not assumed to be economic migrants.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381719","Home Office","false","2015-06-24","<p>The Government has carefully considered the issue of Psychoactive drugs. Last year the Home Office commissioned an expert panel to consider the issue and approaches to tackling New Psychoactive Substances (NPS).</p><p>The NPS expert panel carefully considered the available evidence of different legislative approaches to tackling New Psychoactive Substances. Informed by the evidence on new psychoactive substances and responding to the ease of their availability in the absence of a comprehensive legal framework, the Panel recommended the Government consider a blanket ban similar to the general prohibition approach in Ireland, enacted by their Criminal Justice (Psychoactive Substances) Act 2010. Recognising that the legislative approach alone was not a panacea the panel also considered the education, prevention and treatment response to NPS and made a series of comprehensive recommendations. A report by an expert panel in Scotland in February 2015 and a Welsh Government inquiry by the Health and Social Care Committee in the National Assembly for Wales which reported in March 2015 reached similar conclusions.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-06-24T13:52:57.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381719/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381719/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-17","Drugs: Misuse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what evidence they have that prohibition reduces the consumption of psychoactive drugs.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381720","Home Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>The United Kingdom has a proud tradition of providing protection to those who need it and we will continue to fulfil our responsibilities to those who arrive in the UK and claim asylum.</p><p>However to be eligible for international protection under the 1951 Refugee Convention, a person must be located outside their country of origin. We cannot undertake to consider granting asylum to individuals or groups of people abroad and it is not our practice to grant visas for the purpose of seeking asylum. It is understood that Mr Badawi’s wife and children have been given asylum in Canada.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-06-29T10:55:54.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381720/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381720/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-17","Raif Badawi","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to follow the government of Canada in offering asylum to Raif Badawi.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381721","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2015-07-01","<p>The House’s Estate has been carefully managed over the last fifteen years to enable the Administration to provide a desk to all Members who need one, whilst pursuing objectives of good management of property and value for money, and working within agreed property benchmarking and space targets.</p><p>Desks are allocated to the party groups by the Accommodation Steering Group (a sub-group of the Administration and Works Committee) and it is the responsibility of the party groups to allocate desks to specific members. The Administration seeks to provide desks for a few members who are non-affiliated or who belong to smaller groups not represented in the Usual Channels.</p>",,"Lord Sewel",,"2015-07-01T15:46:48.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381721/answer","Biography information for Lord Sewel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381721/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2015-06-17","Peers","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees what plans there are for providing adequate accommodation for any new members of the House of Lords.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL574"
