"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381781","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-25","<p /> <p>Improving English and maths is a top priority for Government.</p><p>40% of pupils do not get GCSE grades A* to C in English and maths by age 16. Worse still, 90% of those who don’t reach this basic standard by 16, don’t achieve it by age 19.</p><p>The Government is determined to ensure that all students who do not attain A*-C in English and maths GCSEs in KS4 are supported to continue to work towards these vital qualifications.</p><p>From August 2014 students who did not achieve A*-C in English and/or maths GCSE by age 16 must continue to work towards achieving these qualifications or an approved interim qualification as a ‘stepping stone’ towards GCSE as a condition of student places being funded.</p><p>With effect from August 2015, we will amend the funding condition, so full-time 16 to 19 students with prior attainment of grade D in English and/or maths will take GCSE, rather than any other qualification in these subjects.</p><p>For adults without a A*-C GCSE or a level 2 qualification in English and/or maths, the Government will fully fund English and maths provision up to and including level 2. English and maths are also embedded in our training programmes, such as apprenticeships and traineeships, for those who do not have a GCSE A*-C (Level 2 qualification). The skills funding letter for 2015-2016 emphasised the priority we attach to English and maths and spend has been protected through our allocations methodology.</p><p>To address the increase in post-16 students continuing their English and maths study, the Government is investing over £30m over two years (financial years 13/14 and 14/15) in a range of measures to improve the quantity of teachers and quality of teaching and learning practice. To date this investment has supported the recruitment of 680 new graduate teachers and the training of 3,250 existing maths and English teachers.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-06-25T15:03:40.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381781/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381781/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-17","Basic Skills: Further Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what financial resources the Government plans to allocate for the provision of basic English and mathematics in further education.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","2973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381782","Department for Education","false","2015-06-23","<p>It is essential that all young people leave school fully prepared for life in modern Britain. All schools should have a clear strategy for careers guidance which inspires pupils about a range of ambitious careers. We have set this expectation through revised statutory guidance, which underpins schools’ duty to secure independent careers guidance. In addition, a new employer-led Careers and Enterprise Company will encourage greater collaboration between schools and colleges and employers, helping young people to access the best advice and inspiration.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Careers Service provides over 1 million people annually with impartial and professional careers information advice and guidance to help them enter work, learning or progress in life. Last year the National Careers Service went through a complete reconfiguration with all its contracts procured through a comprehensive open and competitive tendering process. The new contracts awarded in October 2014 are on a payment by results basis. 94% of face-to-face and telephone customers agreed that the overall quality of the service was good.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-06-23T14:15:08.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381782/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381782/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-17","Vocational Guidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to improve the performance of careers services.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","2994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381783","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-24","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer that I gave to the Rt Hon. Member for Newcastle upon Tyne East on 15 June 2015, PQ 1799.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-24T11:06:05.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381783/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381783/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-17","Seals: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will bring forward proposals to implement a ban on the killing of seals; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","2988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381784","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-23","<p>The attached table shows how many measures of each type have been installed by region using Green Deal Finance up to end March 2015, based on the number of Green Deal Plans that were ‘live’ by the end of April 2015. This was reported in Table 3a in the following National statistic release:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/green-deal-and-energy-company-obligation-eco-monthly-statistics-may-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/green-deal-and-energy-company-obligation-eco-monthly-statistics-may-2015</a>.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-23T14:53:54.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381784/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381784/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-17","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many measures of each type in each region have been installed under the Green Deal since it was introduced.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","2966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381785","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-23","<p>The Department reported there were 6,809 unique households that had taken out ‘live’ Green Deal Plans at the end of March 2015, (i.e. Plans with measures installed) as reported in Table 1.7 of the following National Statistics release:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/green-deal-energy-company-obligation-eco-and-insulation-levels-in-great-britain-quarterly-report-to-march-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/green-deal-energy-company-obligation-eco-and-insulation-levels-in-great-britain-quarterly-report-to-march-2015</a></p><p>The initial Green Deal finance loan values associated with these Plans at the end of March 2015 was estimated in the order of around £26.5m (excluding APR payments, i.e. the original loan amount). A breakdown by region is shown in the table below:</p><p><strong><em>Table A: The number of 'live' Green Deal Plans and initial loan amounts by Region, up to 31st March 2015</em></strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong><em>Number of Live Plans</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>Initial Loan Amount (£)*</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Great Britain</p></td><td><p>6,809</p></td><td><p>26,460,000</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>3,362</p></td><td><p>11,390,000</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>692</p></td><td><p>2,460,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>718</p></td><td><p>2,510,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and The Humber</p></td><td><p>606</p></td><td><p>1,760,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>428</p></td><td><p>1,510,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>250</p></td><td><p>800,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East</p></td><td><p>188</p></td><td><p>650,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>71</p></td><td><p>170,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>108</p></td><td><p>240,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>301</p></td><td><p>1,300,000</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>328</p></td><td><p>1,300,000</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>3,119</p></td><td><p>13,780,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>*Rounded to nearest ten thousand.</em></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-23T14:52:51.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381785/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381785/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-17","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the value of loans is made under the Green Deal in each region since that scheme was introduced.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","2965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381786","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-23","<p>The Department reported on 18th June 2015, the number of 'live' Green Deal Plans (i.e. Plans with measures installed) by Region, up to 31st March 2015, in Table 1.7 of the following National Statistics release:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/green-deal-energy-company-obligation-eco-and-insulation-levels-in-great-britain-quarterly-report-to-march-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/green-deal-energy-company-obligation-eco-and-insulation-levels-in-great-britain-quarterly-report-to-march-2015</a>.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-23T14:52:25.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381786/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381786/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-17","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many loans have been made in each region under the Green Deal since it was introduced.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","2964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381787","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-25","<p>The number of (a) desktop, (b) laptop and (c) tablet computers that were reported as lost in 2013, 2014 and 2015 to date is set out in the tables. The figures provided are for the entire Department including its executive agencies.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All DfT laptops have full disc encryption to approved Government standards, so it is virtually impossible to recover any data from them without additional hardware and passwords.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>2015</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Item</p></td><td><p>Lost</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Desktop</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Laptops</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Tablet</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p><strong></strong></p><p> </p><p><strong></strong></p><p>2014</p><p><strong></strong></p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Item</p></td><td><p>Lost</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Desktop</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Laptops</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Tablet</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p><strong></strong></p><p> </p><p><strong></strong></p><p>2013</p><p><strong></strong></p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Item</p></td><td><p>Lost</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Desktop</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Laptops</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Tablet</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p /><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-25T10:13:18.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381787/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381787/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-17","Department for Transport: Computers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many (a) desktop, (b) laptop and (c) tablet computers his Department has lost in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","2939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381788","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-26","<p>Vehicles that have been clamped or impounded as a result of an administrative error are released free of charge. There are currently no plans to alter the appeals process.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Complainants can ask for their case to be referred to the Department’s Independent Complaints Assessor or to the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-26T11:07:24.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381788/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381788/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-17","Immobilisation of Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will introduce a right of appeal to a body outside the DVLA for drivers whose car was clamped or towed because  they failed to comply with the changes to the rules on tax discs, or who did comply but this was not noted because of an administrative error by the DVLA.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","2889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381789","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-22","<p /> <p>Under the Social Security (Notification of Deaths) Regulations 2012 and s125 of Social Security Administration Act 1992, individual level death registration information of date of death, is provided to the Department so that appropriate action can be taken with their benefit. Additionally next of kin also provide information on the date of death of an individual. This information is not routinely compiled or published.</p><p> </p><p>Ministers specify the subjects on which they would like any new statistics to be produced and the Head of Profession for Statistics decides how the statistics will be produced and published in an impartial and objective manner.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics should be published as soon as the Head of Profession for Statistics deems they are ready and of the right quality, pre-announcing the publication in accordance with the UK Statistics Authority codes of practice. DWP Statistical releases are produced and published separately to and independently from other Departmental comment or publications.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-22T14:39:50.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381789/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381789/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-17","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what statistics his Department collects on deaths of benefit claimants; and how it is decided and by whom in his Department which statistics on such claimants will be (a) collected and (b) published.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","2905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381790","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-22","<p /> <p>Following the request made on the 25 June 2013 the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) contacted the Department on 19 Sept 2013. The Department replied and the ICO issued a Decision Notice on 27 Nov 2013. On 23 Dec 2013 the ICO notified the Department that the complainant had made an application to appeal the decision notice. The Department decided not to join the appeal and the First Tier Tribunal decision, dated 14 May 2014, was to dismiss the appeal.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-22T14:41:32.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381790/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381790/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-17","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions his Department has had with the Information Commissioner on the Freedom of Information request on deaths of benefit claimants made on 25 June 2013.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","2906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381791","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-22","<p /> <p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given on the 6 November 2014 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=QuestionsWithAnswersOnly&amp;house=commons,lords&amp;dept=29&amp;uin=212728" target="_blank">UIN 212728</a>.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-22T14:33:38.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381791/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381791/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-17","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants of (a) employment and support allowance and (b) incapacity benefit who were (i) in the assessment phase, (ii) found fit to work, (iii) placed in the work-related activity group, (iv) placed in the support group and (v) with an appeal pending have died in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","2955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381792","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-23","<p>These are obviously important issues for both the Welsh Assembly and Scottish Governments, and the local authorities who are affected.</p><p>In neither case is there a legal responsibility on the UK Government to meet the costs of restoring surface mine sites.</p><p>Notwithstanding, I am aware that HM Treasury colleagues are considering proposals put forward for tax exemption related funding in relation to Scotland to address the remediation of former surface mine sites of now insolvent companies. The issues in Wales, although they also relate to remediation, are different in that the relevant site owners are still in existence.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-23T14:35:24.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381792/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381792/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-17","Opencast Mining","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what plans she has to tackle risks associated with disused open cast mines; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","2980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381793","Church Commissioners","false","2015-06-22","<p>The General Synod of the Church of England is committed to the whole Church reducing its carbon footprint. One strategy which is proving popular in local communities is for the Church to use solar installations on its roof to generate energy for the benefit of the surrounding community.</p><p>Examples where community generation is working well can be found in St John's Church, Old Trafford and St George's Church, Kemp Town, Brighton where both churches are part of an energy cooperative. The Church of England is committed to environmental action and finding creative solutions to reduce the energy demands of its own buildings, more detailed advice can be found at <a href="http://www.churchcare.co.uk/" target="_blank">www.churchcare.co.uk</a></p><p><br></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman",,"2015-06-22T13:17:47.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381793/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381793/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2015-06-17","Churches: Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, what proposals the Church Commissioners have received to allow community energy generation using church roofs for solar panels.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","3028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381794","Church Commissioners","false","2015-06-22","<p>The Church of England’s Church Buildings Division offers advice and support to churches across the country who are seeking to generate energy from their roof. While this may not be appropriate for all sites there are a growing number of listed church buildings, currently over 200, who have successfully managed to install solar panels. One of the best examples of the use of solar panels is the 10th century All Saints Church in Wing, Buckinghamshire which has installed solar panels on the nave and south aisle roofs. More detailed advice can be found at <a href="http://www.churchcare.co.uk/" target="_blank">www.churchcare.co.uk</a></p><p> </p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman",,"2015-06-22T13:12:53.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381794/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381794/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2015-06-17","Churches: Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, what support she is providing to churches for the installation of PV panels.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","2916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381795","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-24","<p>We will set out further details on the criteria to be applied in the Housing Bill in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2974","2015-06-24T11:43:08.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381795/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381795/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-17","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether council houses (a) whose value exceeds the median value for properties of the same size in the same region and (b) the value of which is in the top third of the range will be included in the planned extension of the right-to-buy scheme for housing association tenants.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381796","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-24","<p>The Department does not forecast affordable housing delivery by locality by year. The Government is committed to deliver 275,000 affordable homes in England across 2015-20 with £38 billion of public and private investment.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-24T11:35:20.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381796/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381796/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381796/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-17","Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of affordable homes that will be (a) started and (b) completed in (i) Greenwich and Woolwich constituency, (ii) the Royal Borough of Greenwich, (iii) Greater London and (iv) England in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381797","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-24","<p>Statistics on the number of vacant local authority owned dwellings by each local authority district from 2004 to 2014 are published by the Department in Live Table 615 which is available at</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants</a></p><p> </p><p>Statistics are not compiled on the basis of parliamentary constituencies.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-24T11:39:19.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381797/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381797/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-17","Council Housing: Empty Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many council-owned properties have become vacant in (a) Greenwich and Woolwich constituency, (b) the Royal Borough of Greenwich, (c) Greater London and (d) England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381798","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-22","<p>The development of the policy is ongoing, and details will be set out in the impact assessment when the Housing Bill is published.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2972","2015-06-22T15:32:15.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381798/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381798/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-17","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the projected number of housing association tenants that will meet the eligibility criteria for discounts offered under the planned extension of the right-to-buy scheme to housing association tenants in each of the first five years after the introduction of that policy in (a) England, (b) Greater London and (c) Greenwich and Woolwich constituency.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381799","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-01","<p>Statistics on annual Right to Acquire sales for England are published in the Department’s live table 677 which is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-social-housing-sales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-social-housing-sales</a>. <br><br>In addition, the Greater London Authority holds data for the Royal Borough of Greenwich and Greater London from 2012/13 to 2014/15. These figures are provided in the table below. Statistics are not available on a comparable basis for earlier years. The statistics are not compiled on the basis of parliamentary constituencies.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td colspan="2"> </td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Borough of Greenwich</p></td><td> </td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td colspan="2"> </td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater London</p></td><td> </td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>42</p></td><td><p>69</p></td><td colspan="2"> </td></tr><tr><td><p>Source: Greater London Authority</p></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><br><br></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-07-01T15:59:41.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381799/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381799/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-17","Right to Acquire Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many housing association properties were sold under Right to Acquire provisions in each year since 2010 in (a) Greenwich and Woolwich constituency, (b) the Royal Borough of Greenwich, (c) Greater London and (d) England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381800","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-23","<p>Officials have met with a number of housing associations on an individual basis and further meetings are planned.<br><br>Details of Ministers’ meetings and those of the Permanent Secretary with external organisations are published on-line here:<br> <br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-ministerial-data" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-ministerial-data</strong></a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dclg-permanent-secretary-data-2014#history" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dclg-permanent-secretary-data-2014#history</strong></a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-23T11:54:25.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381800/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381800/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-17","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with the G15 group of London housing associations on the potential effects of the planned extension of the right-to-buy scheme for housing association tenants.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381801","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-22","<p>The development of the policy is ongoing, and details will be set out in the impact assessment when the Housing Bill is published.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2978","2015-06-22T15:32:15.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381801/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381801/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-17","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the average sale price per property of houses to be sold under the proposed extension of the right to buy scheme for housing association tenants.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381802","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-24","<p>We will set out further details on the criteria to be applied in the Housing Bill in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2987","2015-06-24T11:43:08.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381802/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381802/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-17","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of council houses which meet the criteria for sale under the planned extension of the right to buy scheme for housing association tenants; and what estimate he has made of how many of those properties will fall vacant in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381803","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-22","<p>Revised air quality plans for nitrogen dioxide will be published by the end of 2015.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-22T13:25:09.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381803/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381803/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-17","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, on what date she plans to publish a new national air quality plan.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381804","Department of Health","false","2015-06-26","<p>Estimates of the fraction of mortality in English local authority areas and regions attributable to long-term exposure to particulate air pollution arising from human activities are published by Public Health England as one of the indicators in the Department’s Public Health Outcomes Framework, which is available at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.phoutcomes.info/search/air%20pollution#gid/1/pat/6/ati/101/page/0/par/E12000007/are/E09000002" target="_blank">http://www.phoutcomes.info/search/air%20pollution#gid/1/pat/6/ati/101/page/0/par/E12000007/are/E09000002</a>)</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Long-term exposure to air pollution is understood to be a contributory factor to deaths from respiratory and cardiovascular disease.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-26T11:47:03.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381804/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381804/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-17","Air Pollution: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of people in London who have died as a result of air pollution in each year since 2010; and if he will estimate the forecast number of such deaths in the next 10 years.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381805","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-24","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my answer of 16 June 2015, UIN 1572, to the Hon Member for Poplar and Limehouse (Mr Fitzpatrick) <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=1572" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=1572</a>.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-24T07:52:18.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381805/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381805/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-17","Exhaust Emissions: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the level of air pollutant emissions from (a) road traffic, (b) aviation and (c) shipping on the air quality in London.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381806","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-23","<p>The Department monitors daily and periodic performance reports from Network Rail and each individual Train Operating Company (TOC) and the information received in the National Rail Passenger Survey, published by Transport Focus, which provides information on passengers’ views on the services of train operators.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-23T14:53:29.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381806/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381806/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-17","Railways: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what (a) research and (b) information his Department holds on the performance of the (i) Southeastern and (b) Southern rail franchises.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381807","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-23","<p>During the last year, I and other transport Ministers have held regular meetings with the representatives of a number of train operating companies, including Southern, Southeastern, South West Trains and Govia Thameslink Railway.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>My first priority in this new parliament is to see performance in the South East improve. We have been working closely with Mark Carne of Network Rail, the operators of Southeastern and Govia Thameslink Railway, and the current (and future) operator of Southern to review the work that Network Rail’s senior team has undertaken on the past few weeks to improve performance in and on their network.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-23T14:02:56.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381807/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381807/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-17","Railways: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what meetings he has had with representatives of rail franchises operating in South London in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381808","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-22","<p>A reply was sent on 22 June.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-06-22T15:39:47.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381808/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381808/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-17","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to reply to the letter to him dated 13 May 2015 from the hon. Members for Aberdeen North, Aberdeen South and West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine regarding an Aberdeen City Region Deal.","false","Biography information for Stuart Blair Donaldson","West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine","Stuart Blair Donaldson","2956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381809","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-10","<p>The Chancellor has announced a new National Living Wage compulsory as of next April, expected to reach £9 an hour by 2020. Tackling low pay is part of the Government's plan to move to a higher wage, lower tax and lower welfare society.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-07-10T08:26:01.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381809/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381809/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-17","Government Departments: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which Government departments are planning to become accredited living wage employers.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","2952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381810","Home Office","false","2015-06-23","<p>The Home Office will not routinely use immigration powers to detain individuals who have been granted refugee status, though may need to do so in specific circumstances, for example if the refugee has subsequently been convicted of committing a crime and deportation action is being taken against them. We would not seek to deport a refugee in such circumstances if they still faced a real risk of death, persecution or torture.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-06-23T15:41:15.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381810/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381810/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-17","Refugees: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the Government's policy is on the detention of refugee women.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","2832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381811","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>I have issued statutory directions or improvement notices in the case of all four authorities found to be in breach of visiting timescales for children privately fostered, requiring improvements to be made. Each has a tailored intervention programme designed to address the weaknesses in children’s services highlighted by Ofsted.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-06-25T12:47:44.513Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381811/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381811/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-17","Foster Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Answer of 26 March 2015 to Question 228386, what steps her Department plans to take in relation to the four authorities found to be in breach of visiting timescales for children in private fostering arrangements.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","2986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381812","Department for Education","false","2015-06-24","<p>The government has made a series of important reforms to improve permanence for looked after children. We gave these reforms a high profile launch at the British Association of Adoption and Fostering conference on permanence in October 2014, where they formed the centrepiece of my speech.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Care Planning and Fostering (Miscellaneous Amendments) Regulations 2015 and associated guidance came into force on 1 April 2015. We have promoted these reforms to local authorities via the Association of Directors of Children’s Services (ADCS) bulletin in March 2015; and again through the Department for Education’s official communication to local authority Directors of Children’s Services, Chief Executives and Lead Members earlier this month.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Care Planning and Fostering (Miscellaneous Amendments) Regulations 2015 have been published online here: <a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2015/495/made" target="_blank">www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2015/495/made</a> and <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/416720/Stat_Guidance_Permanence_2015.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/416720/Stat_Guidance_Permanence_2015.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-06-24T09:31:26.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381812/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381812/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-17","Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if her Department will take steps to raise the profile of the Care Planning and Fostering Regulations and Guidance among local authorities.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","2918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381813","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>In 2013, the Government published the ‘Looked-after children: improving permanence - data pack’. The pack can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/improving-permanence-for-looked-after-children-data-pack" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/improving-permanence-for-looked-after-children-data-pack</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This provides information on children who returned home in 2006 – 2007 and had re-entered care by 2012. The pack illustrates why publishing the rate of re-entry to care for each local authority alone could be misleading. We do not, therefore, have current plans to publish this data. We expect local authorities to be examining their own performance using their data alongside individual children’s case histories.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-06-25T13:16:33.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381813/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381813/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-17","Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy to publish rates of re-entry to care rates in each local authority area.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","2917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381814","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-26","<p /> <p>The Government is considering what further steps would be appropriate to encourage a culture of long-term investment on the part of UK companies and their shareholders. This is important in driving UK productivity and ensuring sustainable economic growth.</p><p> </p><p>We will seek to build on significant progress made in the last Parliament, which included improvements to corporate reporting, and work with companies and investors to encourage the development of good practice for shareholder engagement and stewardship.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-06-26T13:22:54.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381814/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381814/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-17","Shares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he has taken to promote increased long-term share ownership in UK businesses; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","2826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381815","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-26","<p /> <p>Approximately 40% of the UK aerospace sector by employment is foreign owned<strong><sup><strong><sup>[1]</sup></strong></sup></strong>.</p><p> </p><p>Most of the world’s leading aerospace companies have a presence in the UK, including those headquartered overseas.</p><br /><p>[1] BIS analysis of the ONS Inter-Departmental Business Register (IDBR) looking at the ultimate parent of a company to determine ownership</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-06-26T13:18:08.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381815/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381815/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-17","Aerospace Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of the British-based aerospace sector is foreign-owned; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","2827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381816","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-22","<p>Whilst no assessment has been made of the impact of foreign ownership in the aerospace sector on productivity, ONS labour productivity statistics from Q4 2014 show that productivity in the transport equipment sector, which includes aerospace, has been strong relative to the rest of the economy both before and after the financial crisis[1]. Since 2008, output per hour in the sector has grown at a rate of 5% per year. This was the highest rate of growth of any sector in the economy.</p><p> </p><br /><p>[1] ONS (2015) Labour Productivity, Q4 2014</p><p><a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/productivity/labour-productivity/q4-2014/stbq414.html" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/productivity/labour-productivity/q4-2014/stbq414.html</a></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-06-22T16:46:55.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381816/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381816/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-17","Aerospace Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of foreign ownership of UK-based companies on productivity in the aerospace sector; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","2835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381817","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-22","<p>The UK’s traditional openness to trade and investment has served us well. This is increasingly important in a global economy where we compete for new investment and capital.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Certain investments, which may include those by state-owned enterprises or sovereign wealth funds, will be considered by the relevant competition authorities to assess whether they raise competition concerns. If a particular case gives rise to legitimate matters of public interest other than competition, UK Ministers have formal powers to intervene. In addition, the Takeover Panel has effective disciplinary powers and enforcement powers which can be used if it believes the Takeover Code has been contravened.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-06-22T13:36:47.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381817/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381817/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-17","Foreign Companies: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assumptions his Department has made about the powers at its disposal to regulate investments by overseas (a) state-owned enterprises and (b) sovereign wealth funds; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","2838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381818","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-22","<p>As made clear in our white paper National Security Through Technology (Cm 8278) published in February 2012, we will take action in the commercial market place to protect the UK's operational advantages and freedom of action where this is essential for our national security.</p><p>In a free market we welcome both domestic and foreign investment in our defence industry. Assessments of potential risk associated with ownership activity are carried out on a case by case basis.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-22T15:34:16.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381818/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381818/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-17","Defence: Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the potential risks posed to national security by investments in UK defence companies by foreign (a) state-owned enterprises and (b) sovereign wealth funds; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","2837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381819","Home Office","false","2015-06-22","<p>Foreign investment, including into our critical national infrastructure, is vital for our prosperity and this Government welcomes it. We must, though, consider carefully any risks that such investments may present, including to our national security. Prosperity and security are mutually reinforcing. The National Security Council undertakes this important task.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-06-22T15:23:07.14Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381819/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381819/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-17","Infrastructure: Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential risks posed to UK national security by investments in critical national infrastructure by foreign (a) state-owned enterprises and (b) sovereign wealth funds; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","2836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381820","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-22","The Government has no plans to repeal the 1689 Bill of Rights.","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2015-06-22T14:02:00.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381820/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381820/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-17","Bill of Rights 1689","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his policy is on repeal of the 1689 Bill of Rights.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","2932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381822","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-22","<p>The Government welcomes the findings of the Commission’s report into the labelling of meat and religious slaughter, which is a serious contribution to the debate. We are studying the findings and look forward to any proposals that come forward from the EU Commission.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-22T14:25:55.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381822/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381822/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-17","Animal Welfare: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the European Commission's study on information to consumers on the stunning of animals, published in May 2015, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the findings of that report; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Roger Gale","North Thanet","Sir Roger Gale","2954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381823","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-23","<p>Activities at RAF bases made available to the United States Visiting Forces are, and will continue to be, carried out in accordance with both UK and US law.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-06-23T16:23:47.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381823/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381823/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-17","USA: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will take steps to ensure that illegal monitoring of private telecommunications does not take place on US military bases in the UK.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","2919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381824","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-23","<p>DFID’s work in the Occupied Palestinian Territories is channelled through trusted partners including both the UN and non-governmental organisations and mainly consists of large-scale and strategic programmes. The UK Government has made its position on boycotts clear. While we do not hesitate to express disagreement with Israel whenever we feel it necessary, we are firmly opposed to boycotts. We believe that imposing sanctions on Israel or supporting anti-Israeli boycotts would not support our efforts to progress the peace process and achieve a negotiated solution.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-06-23T12:33:21.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381824/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381824/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-17","Israel: Third Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her policy is on providing funding to non-governmental organisations and charities that promote boycotts or sanctions against Israel.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","2940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381826","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-22","<p>Government recognises the importance of science investment in boosting agricultural productivity and growth, which in turn affects competitiveness and real food prices. For firms undertaking research and development (R&amp;D), the Government already has R&amp;D tax credits in place to incentivise this investment. In 2012/13 R&amp;D tax credits provided support to over 15,000 companies, supporting around £13.2bn of innovative investment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Alongside this, the Government’s Agri-Tech Strategy (published July 2013) aims to make the UK a world leader in agricultural technology, innovation and sustainability. This includes allocation of over £320m to further build the pipeline of innovation from the laboratory to the farm; including £70m to support commercialisation projects through the Agri-Tech Catalyst, which the Government continues to invite bids for.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government also announced a further £400m Research Partnership Investment Fund competition at Budget 2015.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-06-22T13:30:37.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381826/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381826/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-17","Agriculture: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what fiscal incentives his Department plans to put in place to stimulate growth in the science and technology industry to support British agriculture.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","2874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381827","Department of Health","false","2015-06-25","<p>Individual plans for 2015-16 are still being developed. It is clear that the National Health Service faces significant financial challenges, due to the increasing demand for health services as a consequence of the ageing and growing population, new drugs and treatments and the need to ensure safer staffing requirements in the wake of Mid-Staffordshire.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This is why we have invested a further £2 billion in the NHS for 2015-16 and the Government has committed to increasing spending on the NHS in real terms every year in this Parliament with spending to be at least £8 billion higher by 2020.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-25T16:21:45.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381827/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381827/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-17","NHS Trusts: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many NHS Trusts and Foundation Trusts have predicted a (a) surplus, (b) break-even position and (c) deficit for the financial year 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","3029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381828","Department of Health","false","2015-06-22","<p>The Department does not have information on the level of National Health Service expenditure on mental health in England in the financial years 2000/01, 2001/02 nor 2002/03. Details of the level of expenditure by the NHS on mental health in England from 2003/04 until 2012/13 is detailed in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Aggregate expenditure on mental health disorders by Primary Care Trust (PCT), for financial years 2003/04 to 2012/13</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Expenditure (£ billion)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003/04</p></td><td><p>6.56</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004/05</p></td><td><p>7.22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005/06</p></td><td><p>7.82</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>8.41</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>9.17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>9.79</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10.</p></td><td><p>10.61</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>10.96</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>11.16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>11.28</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em> </em></p><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> NHS England Programme Budget Data</p><p> </p><p>The information is also available at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.networks.nhs.uk/nhs-networks/health-investment-network/news/2012-13-programme-budgeting-data-is-now-available" target="_blank">https://www.networks.nhs.uk/nhs-networks/health-investment-network/news/2012-13-programme-budgeting-data-is-now-available</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Aggregate PCT expenditure is not yet available for 2013/14. However, NHS England advise that total mental health spending in 2013/14 was £11.362 billion with £11.664 billion planned in 2014/15, an increase of £302 million.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-22T16:48:26.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381828/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381828/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-17","Mental Health Services: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the NHS spent on mental health in England in each year since 2000.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","3040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381829","Department of Health","false","2015-06-22","<p>Total spend on primary care is reported in the Department’s annual accounts. This includes general practice, primary dental services, primary eyecare services, community pharmacy and drugs prescribed in the community.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Expenditure on Primary Healthcare (£000s)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1999-00</p></td><td><p>10,693,377</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2000-01</p></td><td><p>11,449,622</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2001-02</p></td><td><p>12,844,482</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2002-03</p></td><td><p>13,712,439</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003-04</p></td><td><p>14,949,106</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004-05</p></td><td><p>16,598,847</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005-06</p></td><td><p>18,152,704</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>18,630,798</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>19,160,802</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>19,923,424</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>20,870,757</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>21,374,447</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>21,636,558</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>21,431,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The figures are taken from the published National Health Service (England) Summarised Account (1999-2000 to 2010-11) and the Department of Health Annual Report and Accounts (2011-12 and 2012-13).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These figures represent the amount of expenditure on the purchase Primary Healthcare by commissioners. This is in the context that Primary Care Groups (years 1999-2000 to 2001-02), primary care trusts (years 2000-01 to 2012-13) health authorities (years 1999-2000 to 2001-02) and strategic health authorities (years 2002-03 to 2012-13) were responsible for commissioning healthcare from providers based on the needs of their local population.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following the abolition of primary care trusts and strategic health authorities at 31 March 2013 NHS England became responsible for the commissioning of healthcare in England, however, data on primary and secondary healthcare was not collected in 2013-14 by healthcare area and so no data is available for that financial year. Accounts data for the financial year 2014-15 is not yet published.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-22T16:07:59.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381829/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381829/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-17","Primary Health Care: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the NHS spent on primary care in England in each year since 2000.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","3041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381830","Department of Health","false","2015-06-22","<p>Overall National Health Service spend on social care is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-22T16:25:13.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381830/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381830/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-17","Social Services: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the NHS spent on social care in England in each year since 2000.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","3042"
